l>\n<li>Read the text to you. </li>\n</ol>\n<h2>From a web browser, Apple News...</h2>\n<p><strong>How to use:</strong> Choose <code>Share &gt; Read this to me!</code></p>\n<p>The shortcut will:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>Automatically take the URL.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Fetch the article (not the whole web page).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Translate it for you using Microsoft translation service.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Estimate how long it will take to read the article to you.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>After it reads it to you, you can opt to post the link to Facebook or bookmark on <a href=\"https://diigio.com\">diigo.com</a>.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>You can also select part of a web page and Share from there to read just a portion of the web page.</p>\n<h2>From any selected text (email, text editor...)</h2>\n<p><strong>How to use:</strong> Select text, choose <code>Share &gt; Shortcuts &gt; Read this!</code></p>\n<p>The shortcut will:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>Examine the selected text. If it is a URL (if it is, see above, if not, the text itself is the target).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Translate it for you using Microsoft translation service.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Estimate how long it will take to read the article to you.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>From clipboard</h2>\n<p>If you don’t provide a URL or select text, the shortcut will check the clipboard and see if it is a URL or text and follow the flows above. I use this for Facebook posts because Facebook doesn’t have an easy way to share the link to an article. You can easily copy it however.</p>\n\t\t\t\t","releasenotes":"<p><strong>2.10.1 - July 31, 2020, 3:20 p.m.</strong></p><p>Bugfix</p>"}